After total thyroidectomy, hypocalcemia is a common complication due to damage or removal of parathyroid glands. The patient exhibits classic signs of hypocalcemia—perioral numbness, hand spasm (Chvostek sign), fatigue—and has no indication of hypercalcemia or thyroid toxicity. Hypocalcemia leads to increased neuronal excitability and can result in QT interval prolongation on ECG, which increases the risk of lethal arrhythmias such as torsade de pointes. Although torsade de pointes (option A) can occur secondary to hypocalcemia, the direct and most frequently documented ECG change associated with hypocalcemia is **QT prolongation**, making option B the best-supported answer according to multiple sources citing ECG findings in hypocalcemic states.

